
sample_root: Demonstrate root creation at index 3

Two variables, 'pubkey' and 'root_json', are defined in Makefile;  the build
system uses these to generates cri_root symbol for container, which is passed
to cri_create_root() call.

Makefile also defines variable 'footer_json'; the build system uses specified
JSON file to define container permissions.

Although container itself is fairly simple there are several things that should
align for root creation to succeed.
- Root slot must be blank i.e. root must not already exist and must not have
  already been obliterated.
- In container JSON, specified by 'footer_json'
        - Caveats should include 1 (silo).
        - "write_feature_block" permission must include block 0.
        - "establish_roots" permission must include new root's index (3).
        - Defined permissions must be less or equal to container's
          parent root's permissions. Note that variable 'signkey' is not
          defined, as a result container is signed with default private key,
          which belongs to default root (that happens to have full permissions).
- Permissions in JSON specified by 'root_json' must be less or equal to
  permissions in JSON specified by 'footer_json'.

New root's private and public keys are generated using following commands
        openssl ecparam -name prime256v1 -genkey -noout -out privkey.pem
        openssl ec -pubout -in privkey.pem -out pubkey.pem

The generated private key can be assigned to 'signkey' variable in other
container Makefiles, such containers would then belong to root created by this
sample container.

To run (load and start) container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 run sample_root.img

To trigger root creation:
$ echo > one-byte-file
$ cmtest data -f100 one-byte-file

If you trigger root creation again, operation would fail as root slot would no
longer be blank.

To unload container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 unload
